<Base
  title="Mini causal models · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Plant a small causal model with known structure, train on its data, then recover the minimal structure from behavior alone — so the recovery can be scored against a planted truth."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Project · exploratory
    </div>
    <h1>Mini causal models — a sandbox with a known answer</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Plant a small causal model, train on its data, and recover the minimal structure from behavior — where the truth is known.
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Detail page coming.</em> The hard direction in my
      <a href="/writing/inferential-productivity">note on inferential productivity</a> — given a
      behavior, what is the <em>smallest</em> causal structure that has to be there — is hard partly
      because, on a real model, there is no ground truth to check a recovered structure against. So I
      start small and synthetic: plant a causal model whose structure I fully control, simulate data
      from it, train a model on that data, and then try to recover the minimal structure from
      behavior alone.
    </p>

    <MiniCausalFigure />

    <p>
      Because the structure is <em>planted</em>, the recovery can actually be scored — that is the
      whole point of staying synthetic before trusting the method on a real model. It sits between
      <a href="/research/isotrace">Isotrace</a>, which locates <em>where</em> a shortcut replaces
      composition, and <a href="/research/ciy">CIY</a>, which measures <em>how much</em> of a
      structure a model uses: a mini causal model is exactly the kind of structure CIY needs in order
      to read a yield, and this is where I build and stress-test the recovery that produces it.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive sandbox — plant a structure, see what the recovery returns — will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
